# Java Control Statements

## Overview

Control statements are one of the most important concepts in Java because they determine how a program executes. They help us make decisions, repeat tasks, and control the flow of execution based on different conditions.

In real-world applications, control statements are used everywhere—from validating user input and processing data to implementing business logic and handling different scenarios.

Java control statements are broadly classified into three categories:

* Selection (Decision-Making) Statements
* Iteration (Looping) Statements
* Jump Statements

This document covers the core concepts, syntax, examples, interview questions, and frequently asked differences related to Java control statements.

---

## Selection (Decision-Making) Statements

Selection statements allow a program to choose different execution paths based on conditions.

### if Statement

The `if` statement executes a block of code only when the specified condition evaluates to `true`.

```java
int age = 18;

if(age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}
```

### if-else Statement

When there are two possible outcomes, `if-else` can be used.

```java
int age = 16;

if(age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible");
} else {
    System.out.println("Not Eligible");
}
```

### if-else-if Ladder

Used when multiple conditions need to be evaluated sequentially.

```java
int marks = 85;

if(marks >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade A");
}
else if(marks >= 75) {
    System.out.println("Grade B");
}
else {
    System.out.println("Grade C");
}
```

### Nested if

A nested `if` is simply an `if` statement inside another `if` statement.

```java
int age = 20;
boolean hasLicense = true;

if(age >= 18) {
    if(hasLicense) {
        System.out.println("Can drive");
    }
}
```

### switch Statement

The `switch` statement provides a cleaner alternative when multiple cases depend on the same value.

```java
int day = 3;

switch(day) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;

    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
```

Java 14 introduced switch expressions, which are more concise and eliminate the need for explicit `break` statements.

```java
int day = 2;

String result = switch(day) {
    case 1 -> "Monday";
    case 2 -> "Tuesday";
    default -> "Invalid";
};

System.out.println(result);
```

