## Iteration (Looping) Statements

Loops are used when a block of code needs to be executed repeatedly.

### for Loop

Best suited when the number of iterations is known in advance.

```java
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
```

### while Loop

Useful when the number of iterations is not known beforehand.

```java
int i = 1;

while(i <= 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
```

### do-while Loop

Unlike other loops, a `do-while` loop always executes at least once because the condition is checked after execution.

```java
int i = 1;

do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while(i <= 5);
```

### Enhanced for Loop

Commonly used for traversing arrays and collections.

```java
int arr[] = {10, 20, 30, 40};

for(int num : arr) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
```

---

## Jump Statements

Jump statements alter the normal flow of execution.

### break

Used to immediately terminate a loop or switch statement.

```java
for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {

    if(i == 5)
        break;

    System.out.println(i);
}
```

### continue

Skips the current iteration and proceeds with the next iteration.

```java
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

    if(i == 3)
        continue;

    System.out.println(i);
}
```

### return

Terminates a method and optionally returns a value.

```java
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

